{"questionId":"26177","questionHtml":"<p>A simple pendulum has a time period <em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math></em> on the Earth. The pendulum is taken to the Moon&nbsp;where the gravitational field strength is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;that of the Earth.</p>\n<p>What is the time period of the pendulum on the Moon?</p>\n<p>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mi>T</mi></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>T</mi><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>A</p>","meta":{"questionId":"26177","referenceCode":"22M.1.HL.TZ2.29","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"A simple pendulum has a time period T on the Earth. The pendulum is taken to the Moon where the gravitational field strength is 16 that of the Earth. What is the time period of the","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"29","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 9: Wave phenomena","9.1 – Simple harmonic motion","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 9: Wave phenomena"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}